{{infobox bishopstyles |name=Donald Edmond Pelotte |dipstyle=[[The Most Reverend]] |offstyle=[[Your Excellency]] |relstyle=[[Monsignor]] |deathstyle=none }}
'''Donald E. Pelotte''' [[Congregation of the Blessed Sacrament|SSS]] (April 13, 1945 – January 7, 2010) was the third [[Roman Catholic]] [[bishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gallup|Diocese of Gallup]], [[New Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|first=David |last=Cheney |url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bpelotte.html |title=Bishop Donald Edmond Pelotte |publisher=Catholic-hierarchy.org |date= |accessdate=June 27, 2013}}</ref> He was the first person of Native American descent to become a Catholic bishop in the United States; Philadelphia Archbishop [[Charles J. Chaput]], [[O.F.M. Cap.]], is the only active American diocesan bishop of Native American descent.<ref>[http://www.archden.org/index.cfm/ID/272/Archbishop's-Biography-/ Biography and Curriculum Vitae of Charles J. Chaput, O.F.M. Cap., D.D.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724074310/http://www.archden.org/index.cfm/ID/272/Archbishop's-Biography-/ |date=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> He is also the only known Roman Catholic bishop to have ordained his own twin brother. Bishop Pelotte ordained Father Dana F. Pelotte, SSS, to the priesthood, on September 4, 1999 in their childhood parish of [[Waterville, Maine]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Brotherly+love.-a055881932| title=Brotherly love - Bishop Donald E. Pelotte ordains twin brother, Dana F. Pelotte | work=[[National Catholic Reporter]] | date=1999-09-17 | accessdate=2008-01-27 | publisher=The Gale Group }}</ref>
==Education== Pelotte was born on April 13, 1945, in [[Waterville, Maine]], to Norris Albert Pelotte and Margaret Yvonne LaBrie Pelotte. His father was a member of the [[Abenaki]] [[First Nations]] [[tribe]] and his mother was of [[French-Canadian]] ([[French-speaking Quebecer|Québécois]]) descent. Donald and his twin brother Dana were the youngest of five brothers. He studied at Eymard Seminary in [[Hyde Park, New York|Hyde Park]], [[New York (state)|New York]] during his high school years. He did his college studies [[John Carroll University]] in [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]] and later completed doctoral studies at [[Fordham University]]. His doctoral dissertation was entitled: ''[[John Courtney Murray]], Theologian in Conflict: Roman Catholicism and the American Experience''. This was later published in book form by [[Paulist]] Press.<ref name="Gallup bio">{{cite web|url=http://www.dioceseofgallup.org/bishop/pelotte.html |title=Most Rev. Donald E. Pelotte |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gallup|Diocese of Gallup]] |accessdate=2008-01-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509122131/http://www.dioceseofgallup.org/bishop/pelotte.html |archivedate=May 9, 2008 }}</ref>
At age 33, he became the [[Provincial Superior]] of the [[Congregation of the Blessed Sacrament]] and was the youngest major superior of a religious community of men in the United States at the time. On February 24, 1986, he was named [[Coadjutor Bishop]] of Gallup and was consecrated on May 6, 1986. Upon the retirement of [[Jerome J. Hastrich]], then Bishop of Gallup on March 31, 1990, Pelotte became the Third Bishop of Gallup.<ref name="Gallup bio" /> From 1986 to 2008, Pelotte also served as the Episcopal moderator of the [[Tekakwitha Conference]], an association of Native American and First Nation Catholics.<ref>[http://www.tekconf.org/history.html Tekakwitha Conference History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610181704/http://www.tekconf.org/history.html |date=2010-06-10 }}. Retrieved 2008-07-01.</ref>
==Later life== Bishop Pelotte was seriously injured in his Gallup home on July 23, 2007. His injuries included a traumatic [[Traumatic brain injury|brain injury]]. According to chancery officials and a police report, Pelotte insisted his injuries resulted from a fall down his home staircase; however, his aide speculated that he "looked like he'd been beat up" and that his injuries were more consistent with a brutal assault rather than with a fall down a carpeted stairwell.<ref name="Out of ICU">{{cite news | url=http://www.gallupindependent.com/2007/august/080407ehb_bshpmvdfrmicu.html | title=Bishop moved from ICU | author=Elizabeth Hardin-Burrola | work=[[Gallup Independent]] | date=2007-08-04 | accessdate=2008-01-27 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010064842/http://www.gallupindependent.com/2007/august/080407ehb_bshpmvdfrmicu.html | archivedate=2007-10-10 | df= }}</ref>
On January 3, 2008, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] appointed [[Thomas J. Olmsted]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|Bishop of Phoenix]], as [[Apostolic administrator|apostolic administrator ''sede plena'']] of the diocese of Gallup, and granted Pelotte a one-year [[leave of absence]] to continue his recovery.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.gallupindependent.com/2008/January/010408ehb_glpdcsbshpapntd.html | title=Pope steps in | work=[[Gallup Independent]] | date=2008-01-04 | accessdate=2008-01-27 | author=Elizabeth Hardin-Burrola | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080210041123/http://www.gallupindependent.com/2008/January/010408ehb_glpdcsbshpapntd.html | archivedate=2008-02-10 | df= }}</ref>
On April 30, 2008 [[Pope]] Benedict XVI accepted the resignation from the pastoral government of the Diocese of Gallup, presented by Pelotte, SSS, in accordance with canon [http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1E.HTM 401 § 2] of the [[Code of Canon Law]].<ref>[[Cf.]] [http://212.77.1.245/news_services/bulletin/news/22062.php?index=22062&lang=en Holy See Press Office, ''Daily Bulletin of 30.04.2008, Rinunce e nomine, Rinuncia del Vescovo di Gallup (U.S.A.)'']{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{it icon}}</ref> Bishop Olmsted continued to govern the diocese as Apostolic Administrator until [[James S. Wall]] was appointed bishop of Gallup and took canonical possession of the Diocese on 23 April 2009.
On Monday, July 8, 2008, [[KRQE]] News 13 in [[Albuquerque]] and the Gallup Independent newspaper released the results of their investigation of the Pelotte case. Pictures that had not been previously released to the public suggested that the bishop suffered severe blows to the head and back. The station speculated that the injuries did not indicate a fall, but rather a possible beating. The police investigation was closed, though, having never been recalled.<ref>{{cite news|last=HardinBurrola|first=Elizabeth|title=Photos of Bishop Donald E. Pelotte/Pelotte Plight compared to Jesus Crucifixion|url=http://www.bishop-accountability.org/news5/2008_08_01_Hardin_Burrola_PelotteYou.htm|accessdate=1 September 2013|newspaper=The Gallup Independent|date=1 August 2008}}</ref>
Pelotte was hospitalized in critical condition, with his relatives at his side, on December 30, 2009. He died on January 7, 2010. The Funeral Mass for Bishop Pelotte was held on Thursday, January 14, 2010, at the [[Sacred Heart Cathedral (Gallup, New Mexico)|Sacred Heart Cathedral]] in Gallup. Per his wishes, he was buried in the crypt of the Cathedral.<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Heather|title=Bishop Pelotte remembered in Gallup|url=http://www.krqe.com/news/pueblos-tribes/bishop-pelotte-remembered-in-gallup|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130902170237/http://www.krqe.com/news/pueblos-tribes/bishop-pelotte-remembered-in-gallup|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2 September 2013|accessdate=2 September 2013|newspaper=KRQE Channel 13|date=14 January 2010}}</ref>
