{{Infobox judge |honorific-prefix = |name = Maria Farida Indrati |honorific-suffix = |image = Maria Farida Indrati.JPG |imagesize = |alt = |caption = Official portrait |office = Justice of the Indonesian Constitutional Court |term_start = 2008<!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number--> |term_end = 2009 <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number--> |nominator = <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number--> |appointer = [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] |predecessor = <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number--> |successor = <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number--> |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|06|14}} |birth_place = [[Surakarta]], Indonesia |death_date = |death_place = |restingplace = |restingplacecoordinates = |birthname = |citizenship = |ethnicity = Javanese{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Judging by Her Record}} |nationality = Indonesian |party = |otherparty = <!--For additional political affiliations--> |spouse = |partner = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married--> |relations = |children = |residence = |alma_mater = |occupation = |profession = |cabinet = |committees = |portfolio = |religion = [[Catholic]]{{sfn|Constitutional Court, Maria Farida Indrati}} |signature = |signature_alt = |website = |footnotes = }} '''Maria Farida Indrati''', S.H., M.H. (referred to as '''Farida''';{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}} born 14 June 1949) is a justice of the [[Constitutional Court of Indonesia]] serving her second term. She is currently the only woman among the Court's nine members.
==Biography== Farida was born in [[Surakarta]], [[Central Java]], Indonesia on 14 June 1949;{{sfn|Bahari|2011|p=187}} she is the eldest of eight children born to an ''[[Antara (news agency)|Antara]]'' reporter and his wife.{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}} As a child, she studied under Catholic nuns.{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}} Because she suffered from [[polio]], she initially wanted to be a pianist.{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}} However, due to her father's disapproval, she studied law at the [[University of Indonesia]], receiving a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree in 1975.{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}}{{sfn|Bahari|2011|p=187}} Studying under [[Hamid Attamimi]], the "founder of the Indonesian Constitution Science", she decided to stay in law.{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}}
Farida received her notary public's degree in 1982.{{sfn|Bahari|2011|p=187}} She later received a [[Master of Laws]] degree from the same institution in 1997, finishing her [[Doctor of law|doctorate]] studies in 2002.{{sfn|Bahari|2011|p=187}} She has also taken non-formal courses on law making in [[Leiden]], [[Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam]], [[Boston]], and [[San Francisco]].{{sfn|Bahari|2011|p=187}}
Farida initially worked to draft legislation.{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}}
She first served as a justice of the Constitutional Court after she was requested to do so by President [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] in 2008;{{sfn|Bahari|2011|p=187}} she had previously been asked by eight different women's rights organisations, but had refused.{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Judging by Her Record}} She is the nine-member court's first, as of 2010 only, female justice.{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}}{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Judging by Her Record}} During the constitutional court's appraisal of the [[Bill against Pornography and Pornoaction]], she headed the three member specialty panel.{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}} Of the three, she was the only one to question its necessity, saying that the law was "open to too many interpretations, the definition of pornography [too] ambiguous, ... divisive and bound to be difficult to implement,"{{sfn|Sabarini 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}} and noting that traditional dances like [[Jaipongan]] could fall under its definition.{{sfn|National Commission 2010, Maria Farida Indrati}} She has also dissented in cases regarding blasphemy law and a quota for legislative seats for women.{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Judging by Her Record}} She was initially expected to serve until 2013.{{sfn|Bahari|2011|p=187}}
Yudhoyono attempted to appoint Farida to a second term in 2013, though her reappointment alongside the appointment of colleague [[Patrialis Akbar]] was initially blocked by the Jakarta State Administrative Court.<ref>Ina Parlina , [http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2013/12/24/administrative-court-strips-patrialis-mk-seat.html-0 Administrative court strips Patrialis of MK seat]. [[Jakarta Post]], 24 December 2013. Accessed 17 August 2016.</ref> Yudhoyono's office appealed the ruling on behalf of the two justices,<ref>[http://jakartaglobe.beritasatu.com/news/palace-defends-patrialis-appointment-prepares-appeal/ Palace Defends Patrialis Appointment, Prepares Appeal]. Jakarta Globe, 24 December 2013. Accessed 24 October 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.antaranews.com/en/news/91934/indonesian-govt-considering-appealing-against-verdict-annulling-constitutional-court-justice-appointment Indonesian govt considering appealing against verdict annulling constitutional court justice appointment]. Antara News, 24 December 2013. Accessed 24 October 2016.</ref> succeeding after the Jakarta High Administrative Court found that the petition against the two of them lacked legal standing for the challenge.<ref>Simon Butt, [https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=gWhECQAAQBAJ&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=patrialis+akbar+appeal+court&source=bl&ots=9AVdDArodz&sig=b4-8JZUhHxO1HzcTSKS2NFCXgTQ&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=patrialis%20akbar%20appeal%20court&f=false The Constitutional Court and Democracy in Indonesia], pg. 41. [[Leiden]]: [[Brill Publishers]], 2015. {{ISBN|9789004250598}}</ref> Farida also served on one of three panels set up by the Constitutional Court to investigate former presidential candidate [[Prabowo Subianto Djojohadikusumo]]'s complaint in the [[Indonesian presidential election, 2014]], serving on the panel alongside fellow justices [[Ahmad Fadlil Sumadi]] and [[Aswanto]].<ref>[http://www.antaranews.com/en/news/94002/indonesias-constitutional-court-establishes-panels-to-handle-election-disputes Indonesia's constitutional court establishes panels to handle election disputes]. [[Antara (news agency)|Antara]], 12 May 2014. Accessed 20 October 2016.</ref> The panels ultimately found that the claims of Subianto's campaign were mostly without merit.<ref>Ina Parlina and Hans Nicholas Jong, [http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2014/08/09/prabowo-loses-first-legal-battle.html Prabowo loses first legal battle]. Jakarta Post, 9 August 2014. Accessed 20 October 2016.</ref>
Farida is also a lecturer on legislation at the University of Indonesia; after becoming a constitutional justice, she kept the job because she feared that "if [she did not] teach it would be tempting for [her to] not read or not learn anything new".{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Judging by Her Record}} She is also a guest lecturer at numerous other universities.{{sfn|Bahari|2011|p=187}}
==Views== Farida believes that the [[Constitution of Indonesia]] guarantees equality between Indonesian men and [[Women in Indonesia|women]], but that its application has been lacking.{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Judging by Her Record}} She believes that the traditionally patriarchal culture has limited women's chances by limiting their educational opportunities.{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Judging by Her Record}}
